<doc id="794492" wikidata="Q3229338" url="?curid=794492" title="Fitting lemma">
<text>In mathematics, the Fitting lemma – named after the mathematician Hans Fitting – is a basic statement in abstract algebra. Suppose &quot;M&quot; is a module over some ring. If &quot;M&quot; is indecomposable and has finite length, then every endomorphism of &quot;M&quot; is either an automorphism or nilpotent.

As an immediate consequence, we see that the endomorphism ring of every finite-length indecomposable module is local.

A version of Fitting&#x27;s lemma is often used in the representation theory of groups. This is in fact a special case of the version above, since every &quot;K&quot;-linear representation of a group &quot;G&quot; can be viewed as a module over the group algebra &quot;KG&quot;.

== Proof ==

To prove Fitting&#x27;s lemma, we take an endomorphism &quot;f&quot; of &quot;M&quot; and consider the following two chains of submodules:

* The first is the descending chain formula_1,
* the second is the ascending chain formula_2
Because formula_3 has finite length, both of these chains must eventually stabilize, so there is some formula_4 with formula_5 for all formula_6, and some formula_7 with formula_8 for all formula_9

Let now formula_10, and note that by construction formula_11 and formula_12

We claim that formula_13. Indeed, every formula_14 satisfies formula_15 for some formula_16 but also formula_17, so that formula_18, therefore formula_19 and thus formula_20

Moreover, formula_21: for every formula_22, there exists some formula_16 such that formula_24 (since formula_25), and thus formula_26, so that formula_27 and thus formula_28

Consequently, formula_3 is the direct sum of formula_30 and formula_31. (This statement is also known as the &quot;Fitting decomposition theorem&quot;.) Because formula_3 is indecomposable, one of those two summands must be equal to formula_3 and the other must be the zero submodule. Depending on which of the two summands is zero, we find that formula_34 is either bijective or nilpotent.

